Interview Questions (with Ideal Answers)
Q1. How does @Transactional work internally?

It is implemented using Spring AOP. A proxy intercepts the method call, starts a transaction through the PlatformTransactionManager, executes the business logic, and then commits or rolls back depending on the outcome.

Q2. Why doesn't @Transactional work on private methods?

Because Spring's proxy cannot intercept calls to private methods.

Q3. Why doesn't it work with self-invocation?

A call like this.method() bypasses the Spring proxy, so the transaction interceptor never runs.

Q4. Why don't checked exceptions trigger rollback?

By default, Spring only rolls back for RuntimeException and Error. Use rollbackFor to include checked exceptions.

Q5. Difference between flush() and commit()?
Flush	Commit
Sends SQL statements to the database	Permanently commits the transaction
Can happen multiple times	Happens once per transaction
Changes can still be rolled back	Cannot be rolled back after commit
Q6. Difference between REQUIRED and REQUIRES_NEW?
REQUIRED	REQUIRES_NEW
Joins an existing transaction if one exists	Always starts a new transaction
Default propagation	Suspends the current transaction
Rolls back together with the outer transaction	Commits or rolls back independently
